abstract: The rater has become the rated.
snippet: The rater has become the rated.
lead_paragraph: I’ve been to the bagel place down the street from my apartment maybe a hundred times. The staff is friendly. I like the food. They’re always open.

abstract: Fearing judgment of her interracial relationship and mixed-race child, a woman keeps both from her family. Until she doesn’t.
snippet: Fearing judgment of her interracial relationship and mixed-race child, a woman keeps both from her family. Until she doesn’t.
lead_paragraph: My son, Roman, turned to me from his book and said, “Mom, can you throw me a blanket? This is my favorite part in the book and I don’t want to stop.”

abstract: The stoic feelings of progressive Washington were similarly subdued in the city’s more conservative corners.
snippet: The stoic feelings of progressive Washington were similarly subdued in the city’s more conservative corners.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Outrage, a clothing store in the capital that has branded itself a hub of the resistance to President Trump, is a place where people have often gathered to shed tears over the latest news cycle, or to buy $32 T-shirts emblazoned with expletive-laced messages calling for the president’s impeachment.

abstract: The scholar’s latest book, coinciding with his new PBS series, “Reconstruction,” is a harrowing look at the resurgence of white nationalism in the late 19th century and the New Negro movement to combat it.

abstract: “He’s behaving as the president’s personal lawyer,” Senator Kirsten Gillibrand said. “He’s not behaving as the attorney general of the United States.”
snippet: “He’s behaving as the president’s personal lawyer,” Senator Kirsten Gillibrand said. “He’s not behaving as the attorney general of the United States.”
lead_paragraph: CRESTON, Iowa — Senator Kirsten Gillibrand of New York had just finished a speech at a coffee shop in southwest Iowa on Thursday, one that focused on rural issues like expanding broadband and developing the local economy.

abstract: A new HBO series examines Anne Lister, a 19th-century Englishwoman and landowner who chronicled her romantic relationships with other women in great detail.
snippet: A new HBO series examines Anne Lister, a 19th-century Englishwoman and landowner who chronicled her romantic relationships with other women in great detail.
lead_paragraph: Referring to Anne Lister as a force of nature is accurate, but it’s also just a starting point.

abstract: Willem Baptist’s documentary is an impressionistic study of the end of the Polaroid camera and the “instant film” it used.
snippet: Willem Baptist’s documentary is an impressionistic study of the end of the Polaroid camera and the “instant film” it used.
lead_paragraph: It isn’t often that one watches a film, particularly a documentary, and thinks, “I wish this was more conventional.” Yet that may be your experience of “Instant Dreams,” a picture directed by Willem Baptist about the end of the Polaroid camera and the “instant film” it used.

abstract: Robert Downey Jr. and the Marvel Studios president, Kevin Feige, look back on a time when “Iron Man,” let alone an “Avengers” movie, was hardly a sure thing.
snippet: Robert Downey Jr. and the Marvel Studios president, Kevin Feige, look back on a time when “Iron Man,” let alone an “Avengers” movie, was hardly a sure thing.
lead_paragraph: Today, we think of Marvel as the monolithic studio that each year reliably releases two or three blockbusters based on its costume-clad comic-book superheroes. It has built movies like “Captain Marvel” and “Black Panther” into money-minting franchises, and when its latest offering, “Avengers: Endgame,” is released on April 26, it will conclude a narrative spanning some 22 films that started with “Iron Man” in 2008.

abstract: Bundlers and endorsers are out. Ears and eyeballs are in.
snippet: Bundlers and endorsers are out. Ears and eyeballs are in.
lead_paragraph: The early stages of the 2020 Democratic primary are rewriting the rules of how a candidate wins his or her party’s presidential nomination. Recent Democratic primary battles were all about the invisible primary, the yearlong period before the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary — when presidential candidates hired key staff members, seduced major donors and lined up crucial endorsements.
